<div class='digest-box'>
<h3>Good Morning Singapore</h3>
<p>Kyiv braces for a brutal winter as fears of heating outages grow amid renewed Russian attacks. Off the battlefield, a leaked US draft peace plan would require Ukraine to cede eastern territory and shrink its army, a prospect Kyiv says is hard to swallow while Moscow says it could be a basis for peace if Kyiv agrees. Meanwhile, G20 leaders meet in South Africa trying to push a declaration despite a US boycott, a reminder that Ukraine-related diplomacy keeps dragging global politics into every corner of our lives.</p>
<p>Back home, Singapores economy looks steadier, with the 2025 growth forecast nudged up to about 4% and 2026 expected to ease to 13%. Exporters still face headwinds, with 2026 non-oil export growth pencilled in at around 2.5%. On the market side, SGX plans to cut board lot sizes to boost liquidity, while travel picks up as Changi Airport logs more than 5.8 million passengers in October.</p>
<p>Closer to everyday life, Singapore keeps juggling policy and public concerns: education policy aims for a broader, more inclusive approach beyond pure meritocracy; a gastro outbreak hits six E-Bridge preschools, with Middleton International Schools food supplier suspended; and authorities warn that Singpass-verified Carousell accounts are being misused by scammers. Its a busy weekleaning into big global shifts while we handle the tiny, concrete things that matter to families here.</p>
